<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[213,322,521,545]" box="[213,322,521,545]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[213,322,521,545]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[213,1170,562,777]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
Prostomium entire or incised, extending posteriorly as a caruncle, surrounded by nuchal organ. Chaetiger 1 without notochaetae. Chaetiger 5 greatly modified, with major spines of one 
<typeStatus box="[288,335,625,649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">type</typeStatus>
in a single curved row, usually accompanied by slender companion chaetae. Posterior notopodial spines present or absent. Neuropodial hooded hooks bidentate from chaetigers 7–14, with conspicuous angle between teeth, with constriction on shaft. Branchiae begin posterior to chaetiger 5. Pygidium variable: cuff-shaped, cup-shaped or disc-like with dorsal gap, lobed, scoop-shaped, or with digitiform cirri.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[213,313,833,857]" box="[213,313,833,857]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[213,313,833,857]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[213,1169,874,962]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bosc" authorityYear="1802" box="[213,314,874,898]" class="Polychaeta" family="Spionidae" genus="Polydora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spionida" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[213,314,874,898]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="11">Polydora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Blake JA" box="[519,665,874,898]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="81 - 223" refId="ref7345" refString="Blake JA. 1996. Family Spionidae Grube, 1850, including a review of the genera and species from California and a revision of the genus Polydora Bosc, 1802. In: Blake JA, Hilbig B, Scott PH, editors. Taxonomic atlas of the benthic fauna of the Santa Maria Basin and the Western Santa Barbara Channel. Vol. 6. Santa Barbara (CA): Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History. p. 81 - 223." type="book chapter" year="1996">Blake (1996)</bibRefCitation>
; he divided the species into five groups and recognized 31 species; with the new species described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams JD" box="[832,1011,906,930]" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="429 - 465" refId="ref8810" refString="Williams JD. 2001. Polydora and related genera associated with hermit crabs from the Indo- West Pacific (Polychaeta: Spionidae), with descriptions of two new species and a second polydorid egg predator of hermit crabs. Pacific Science 55: 429 - 465." type="journal article" year="2001">Williams (2001)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Radashevsky VI &amp; Pankova VV" pageId="11" pageNumber="11" pagination="245 - 252" refId="ref8408" refString="Radashevsky VI, Pankova VV. 2006. The morphology of two sibling sympatric Polydora species (Polychaeta: Spionidae) from the Sea of Japan. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom 86: 245 - 252." type="journal article" year="2006">Radashevsky and Pankova (2006)</bibRefCitation>
and Radashevsky et al. (2006), there are now 36 species.
</paragraph>
